    "abstract": "<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>\n                <jats:p>\n                  SARS-CoV-2 remains a worldwide emergency. While vaccines have been approved and are widely administered, these are only available to adults and adolescents in Europe. Therefore, in order to mitigate the spread of more transmissible SARS-CoV-2 variants among children, the use of non-pharmaceutical interventions is still warranted. We investigate the impact of different testing strategies on the SARS-CoV-2 infection dynamics in a primary school environment, using an individual-based modelling approach. Specifically, we consider three testing strategies: 1)\n                  <jats:italic>symptomatic isolation</jats:italic>\n                  , where we test symptomatic individuals and isolate them when they test positive, 2)\n                  <jats:italic>reactive screening</jats:italic>\n                  , where a class is screened once one symptomatic individual was identified, and 3)\n                  <jats:italic>repetitive screening</jats:italic>\n                  , where the school in its entirety is screened on regular time intervals. Through this analysis, we demonstrate that repetitive testing strategies can significantly reduce the attack rate in schools, contrary to a reactive screening approach. Furthermore, we investigate the impact of these testing strategies on the average number of school days lost per child.\n                </jats:p>",
